'''Optibo''' is the product of a collaboration between [[Sweden|Swedish]] firms to solve the [[house|housing]] industry's problem of availability of space caused by high land prices. Optibo's main architect was inspired when he saw the Disney cartoon, [[Mickey's Trailer]], on TV.<ref Name="Gardiner ">{{Citation | last = Gardiner | first = Virginia | author-link = Virginia Gardiner | title = Warmth and Mechanics | pages= 78–80
| edition= 4 | volume= 4 | publisher= Dwell | date = March 2004 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3cEDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA80&dq=Optibo&hl=en&ei=_X6DTb_nEbS80QHb_qzECA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Optibo&f=false | ISSN = 1530-5309 }}</ref>
The project has led to the construction of an [[apartment]] which is only 25 square meters (270 square feet) in area. The single-room living space has the [[furniture]] built into the floor and the room can be changed from a [[living room]] to a [[bedroom]], to a [[dining room]], and back. The [[kitchen]] area is affixed to the wall and does not change. {{fact|date=March 2011}}
